},"en":{"Abt 1183–about 1216":"about 1183–about 1216","1180–1219":"1180–1219","1214–Male":"1214–Deceased","1210–1255":"1210–1255","1212–Male":"1212–Deceased","1216–Female":"1216–Deceased","1183–1216":"1183–1216","Abt 1205":"about 1205","Abt 1216":"about 1216","1183":"1183","1180":"1180","abt 1214":"about 1214","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","Abt 1183":"about 1183","1214":"1214","Abt 1212":"about 1212","1212":"1212","1255":"1255","1210":"1210","about 1216":"about 1216","1219":"1219","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, England","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","Cherlton, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Charlton on Otmoor, Bicester, Oxfordshire, England":"Charlton-on-Otmoor, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","of Cherlton, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","Of Cherlton, Oxford, England":"Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cherlton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Northumberland and Durham): habitational name from North Charlton or Charlton near Bellingham (both Northumberland) or from any of the many other places so named (there are over ninety examples in England), from Old English <i>Ceorlatūn</i> ‘settlement (Old English <i>tūn</i>) of the peasants’. Old English <i>ceorl</i> denoted originally a free peasant of the lowest rank, later (but probably already before the Norman conquest) a tenant in pure villeinage, a serf or bondsman.","Irish: altered form of   Carlin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Carlton","meanings":["English (northern and eastern England): habitational name from any of various places called Carlton (Bedfordshire, Cambridgeshire, Durham, Lincolnshire, Leicestershire, Nottinghamshire, Northamptonshire, Suffolk, East Yorkshire, Yorkshire, and North Yorkshire) or Carleton (Cumberland, Lancashire, Norfolk, Yorkshire). All come from Old Norse <i>karl</i> ‘common man, peasant’ + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’ (compare   Charlton  ). Places spelled <i>Carl(e)ton</i> (as opposed to <i>Charlton</i>) are in areas of Scandinavian settlement, mostly in northern England.","Irish (Antrim): variant of   Carleton   2."]},{"name":"Carlin","meanings":["Irish (North Ulster; now also common in Scotland): from <b>Ó Cearbhalláin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cearbhallán</i>’, a diminutive of the personal name <i>Cearbhall</i> (see   Carroll  ).","English: variant of   Carling  .","Italian (Veneto): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Carlo</i>, Italian form of   Charles  ."]}]},{"name":"Katherine","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: Same as Catherine."],"variants":[]},{"name":"De","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":32,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Katherine De Cherlton was born about 1183, in Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Hugh Poure about 1205, in Charlton-on-Otmoor, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. She died about 1216, in Oxfordshire, England, at the age of 35."},"et":{"Abt 1183–about 1216":"umbes 1183–umbes 1216","1180–1219":"1180–1219","1214–Male":"1214–Surnud","1210–1255":"1210–1255","1212–Male":"1212–Surnud","1216–Female":"1216–Surnud","1183–1216":"1183–1216","Abt 1205":"umbes 1205","Abt 1216":"